fields.title: Dino Capitalism
fields.description:
Dino Capitalism
============

Dino capitalism is a game about.. well... capitalism! 

Key features
----------------
* There is no goal. Just make money.
* There is no balance. Everything is broken.
* Dinosaurs

Instructions
--------------
* You can buy upgrades in the bottom left.
* All of the data you need to know is on the top of the game.
* Events will happen every minute. They are displayed in the red text at the bottom of the screen.
* Taxes affect your overall profits. Try to reduce them or find another way to offset them.
* Factories reduce the batch time by .1 seconds, to a minimum of 2 seconds per batch.
* Workers create dinos based on their productivity( 2D Means 2 dinos per worker, per batch ).
* Your dinosaur prices can be increased through various upgrades to the dinosaurs themselves.

I may update this some more before the contest is up. I had alot of fun making it, and it is the first game I have ever finished.

fields.title: Switch: Interdimensional Puzzling!
fields.description:
Hey Everyone,

Thank you for checking out my entry! This game "Switch: Interdimensional Puzzling!" is my FIRST EVER released title, so I am really excited to be able to bring it to you. It's been a lot of work. 25+ Hours across the two days, and a bunch of headaches, plus a last minute mechanic scrap because Game Maker refused to work, but after all that, I'm happy with the final product. (Could do without the "Made With Game Maker Light" watermark, though.)

Switch is a game about speedrunning through levels, completing tasks in a particular order in order to move through the levels. Discovering which routes or techniques are fastest, how to use and abuse the collision/physics engine, and trying to figure out which tasks are necessary/worth doing will all help you get the fastest time.

There are a few bugs and errors, and the collision system is meh, but I actually think that the collision makes the game better in a way, allows for a little but more free, not so rigid movement system, where some of the rules of how to move are determined by how you play (If that makes sense to anyone but me.) 

Controls:

Arrow Keys Or WASD: Move

Space: Swap Worlds

Enter: Go Through Door

May continue this game, will probably be making a Post-Mortem, and will fix any bugs or errors that are brought to my attention to help the game play better. (You can send bugs, etc to 0CredsMail@Gmail.com) The person to post of screencap of the end screen with the lowest score + highest gems by Monday will be given 2500 Creds ($25.00) to spend @ 0credsstore.tumblr.com (Please don't break the game or use Photoshop, I'm trying to make things fun for you all, and all I ask is that you don't take advantage of my kindness.)

The First Link Below Is The COMPO Version, The Second Will Be The Continually Updated POST COMPO Version. (There are a few bugs in the first version, mainly, the game doesn't note your score.) (Cause I'm an idiot) (And cause I forgot to check "Visible")... #WhyIDoDis

Thanks Again Everyone,

- 0Creds

fields.title: A Peasant's Tale (My RPG) Combat System
fields.description:
Ok so this was my first LWIMW. In fact, this was actually my first jam ever so yay!

This weekend, I made the combat system for my 2D RPG called A Peasant's Tale. I'm really happy with what I got done since I did even more than what I originally set out to do in the first place. I added a health system, created an entity removal system, made it so that when an entity is killed it is removed from the level, added sounds for hitting an enemy and being hit, added knockback for hitting enemies, added a blocking mechanic, and made blood particles shoot out of something (the player or the enemy) when it is hit.

The only thing I didn't get to was making good art for everything (I just threw together some basic coder art), but I'm really not too worried about that since I really just wanted to focus on coding the actual mechanics of everything.

Overall, this was a great weekend and I can't wait for LWIMW IV.

I wasn't able to make a submission video in time, but I'll definitely put one up on Monday, so I'll link you guys to my Youtube channel so you can check it out when it's uploaded (also feel free to look at all my other development videos of my game). :)

And, yes, the enemies are squids, cuz why not? :P

Source is available on Githhub.  Unfortunately there isn't really anything to see, so you'll have to take my word for it that it is "really really good."

fields.title: Rhythmic Asteroids

Have you ever wanted to play the best game ever? A game with asteroids made out of cotton candy? Repetitive drum beats? Flying chainsaws (or flowers, depending on who you ask)? This is all of those things. Prepare to get partially excited!

You are a spaceship. Shoot anything that's not a spaceship. Eventually all that will be left is your spaceship.

Movement: WASD
Aiming: Mouse
Fire: Left click
Charge fire: Right click

Each wave will place a number of asteroids in the arena equal to the wave number plus 4.  You have 2 seconds of invincibility while the blue sphere is up.  Tap the charge fire (right click) button to the kick drum beat to charge up your energy level.  If you are on the beat you will fire a small shot and get 1 energy, if you are too far off the beat, you will lose an energy.  Fire with left click to unleash an attack that is larger the more energy you have.

Note that asteroids have health, and must be shot at a few times to break.

Link 1 is the web version, link 2 is native Windows, Mac, and Linux builds.

A collaboration between Atmospherium and DVColgan.

fields.title: What Teh FAK Did I Do?

fields.body:
I finished my game, "Dino Capitalism", pretty early on this weekend, with 24 hours left to go. It is actually the first game that I have finished to a point where it's playable and actually somewhat fun.You can vote on it [here](http://lookwhatimadeweekend.com/contest/1/submission/32/).

What went right
-------------------
Actually, alot went right, which surprised me. When I attempted ludum dare for the first time last summer, I didn't do well at all and had to drop out of the compo. This time around, I was on a roll, 24/7, with little to no interruption. I had a solid theme, right off the bat, and that was capitalism. I wanted to make some form of cookie clicker-esque tycoon game, with more of a focus on finances and money. I got off and started very quickly, and even got some art done which I was very proud of. I am a horrible artist, I don't even know how I was able to paint that decent dinosaur. I managed my priorities, got all the features I wanted implemented, and I got it done quickly. I even managed to make my scripts pretty clean.

What went wrong
---------------------
This morning, I woke up and I decided that I didn't like where my game was headed. I changed it to a first person shooter, decided that wasn't fun, and then moved onto a straight up top down tycoon game. I lost a few precious hours on that, and nearly got demotivated. The biggest problem I ran into though, was Unity. I think after this weekend, I am done with Unity3D for good. The lack of a proper GUI system was nearly when I gave up on the weekend. I was trying desperately to make a GUI system that looked good and could convey information but I just couldn't get it to look well in a small browser window. Eventually I had to compromise and just used plain text with an alright font for the GUI. I wish I could make it better, which I think would make the game alot better, because of all the numbers and data that actually goes into finding the final profit. The other thing that went wrong was the balance of the game. Tomorrow I may go back and fix it up a bit, but it's very easy to get negative taxes and make billions of dollars just by buying a bunch of water coolers. I also wish I could make a better item system that is more modular, but again this is held back by Unity's GUI.

Conclusion
--------------
I am probably done with my submission. The most I will do is go back tomorrow and make a few bug fixes. I honestly can't stand to use Unity anymore, but after using it for years and running into all of these problems over and over again, I think it's time to move onto greener pastures. I really enjoyed working on my submission though. I hope that we can have another LWIMW again soon, and good luck to all who are still working on their submissions.

A quick note to david - Great job on the site. Thank you for hosting it, and hosting this game jam. I had alot of fun, and I can't wait to see what everyone comes up with,and do it again. I'm sure all of us who participated are grateful to you for taking the time to do this. I hope you add the ability to view my own submission page and send links to single posts though :) 

Here is the games [source code and source unity project](http://bit.ly/1hjso8X).

fields.body:
Intro

Just Finished "Switch: Interdimensional Puzzling" And Not A Moment Too Soon! With merely 2 whole minutes left in the Compo, the game was completed, and the submission process begun. I spent a total of about 25+ Hours on the game as a whole, and I'm really happy with the final product.

What Went Right

Well, being my first successful Game Jam, I'd say a lot wen't right. Although I had to scrap a mechanic at the end because Game Maker refused to work, I am still happy with the way the game turned out. I had trouble with a lot, more than I should have, but through all the headaches, I finished the project, and completed something that was more polished than I thought it would. Overall, not EVERYTHING went right, but at the same time, I'm not at all disappointing with my work.

What Went Wrong

This morning I woke up late, I intended to wake up at around 8 to give myself a good 13 hours before submissions, but I ended up waking up at 12:30 instead, and after breakfast, I found myself sitting at 1:00. I got right to work, but I worked a solid 8 hours until 9:00, and working yourself that hard can never be good. So I'll probably take a short break from Game Dev and streaming for a while, maybe about a week, play some Pokemans, enjoy some time on Skype with friends and stuff, (Y'know, normal stuffs that normal peoples do when they aren't making games :D) Virtually nothing went wrong accept for time, and my iffy knowledge on GML going into this game made things slightly more difficult, but I ended up pulling through.

Conclusion

I'm gonna be updating my submission after my break most likely, but I have a ton of other projects that I'm working on too, so no promises there. I'll fix any bugs, etc that are brought to my attention, and I hope that everyone who plays has as much fun playing it as I did making it. As my first released title I think that it is something to be proud of, and will hopefully give you an idea of what types of games you'll be seeing from me in the near future. Thanks for reading, and I can't wait to play all of your submissions. Also, special thanks to DV for hosting this Jam, I'll never forget where I made my first game.

Each box is a physics world and a physics body inside another world. The six squares being displayed are six instantiated boxes. The angled lines indicate parent-child relationships between boxes. The little square in box #0 is a movable object (the player, I suppose).

Right now, there are six small textures residing on the graphics card, to which each box renders. This should make it simpler to render movable objects which are partially between boxes.

The idea I'm working towards is a system supporting smooth physical and graphical transitions as the player or other movable objects traverse the box-tree.

The goal of this weekend is to finish the tank for my solar water heater. Before this weekend, I had the majority of the tank built, but I still needed to line the inside with an EPDM liner, fill it with water, and build the lid that goes on top.

My other goal is to cut and solder together some copper pieces that will attach to the pump (which I don't have yet) and also attach the 300' PEX heat exchanger to the incoming water supply to the hot water.

Wooden tank in place hear the hot water heater, with the EPDM liner sitting inside. This is where all the solar energy will be stored in the form of hot water. A heat exchanger will sit inside the tank and preheat the well water going to the hot water heater.

![view of tank](http://i.imgur.com/OLYSPOs.jpg) 

View inside the tank, with a few inches of water in the bottom. I will need to get the liner all folded up nicely and make sure it won't stretch when I put the rest of the water in.

![inside the tank](http://i.imgur.com/h2AKN7h.jpg)

The lid will be composed of 1/2" plywood sandwiched between 2" of Polyiso insulation on either side. I had to glue together two separate pieces of EPDM liner, which is why the cinder blocks are sitting on top. The cinder blocks will sit inside the tank and support the heat exchanger when the tank is empty.

![Pieces of the lid](http://i.imgur.com/li8Wisz.jpg)

2" of polyiso insulation ready to be glued together with insulating foam sealant.

![Insulation cut and ready to glue](http://i.imgur.com/u1U7l60.jpg)
